<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="83" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1437,151,1187]" pageId="38" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1018,1043]" pageId="38" pageNumber="83">Comments</emphasis>
: The contrasting dark lower vitta and flanking yellow lower orbits are distinctive, as is the apically dark hind femur and the diffuse central wing infuscation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="83" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1437,151,1187]" pageId="38" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1091,1115]" pageId="38" pageNumber="83">Etymology</emphasis>
: The specific epithet is from the Greek 
<emphasis box="[848,915,1091,1115]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="83">
<taxonomicName box="[848,911,1091,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Grallipeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turba">turba</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
for “tumult or disorder”, referring to the consternation caused when these specimens turned up amongst a large series of the common Dominican species 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="83">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Grallipeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinuliger">G. spinuliger</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[275,463,1163,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Grallipeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turba">Grallipeza turba</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
appears to be most closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[884,1008,1163,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Grallipeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="baracoa">
<emphasis box="[884,1008,1163,1187]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="83">G. baracoa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1062,1202,1163,1187]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="83">
<taxonomicName box="[1062,1198,1163,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Grallipeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nebulosa">G. nebulosa</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
